<br>
I can't test it right now... but I know that to format a disk there's a new wizard. It should allow you to create an EBD (Emergency Boot Disk). Just open up My Computer by clicking Start &gt; My Computer. Right click on the 3.5&quot; Floppy, and choose Format...<br>
<br>
You can also create the EBD from Whizbang's W9X machine, in the Add/Remove programs control panel, under &quot;Startup Disk&quot;. I would reccomend that you include Ranish Partition Manager on the disk or another floppy. There's a link to it later.<br>
<br>
Once you've created the EBD, reboot with the disk in the drive. You'll want to use 2 programs to wipe the disk completely....<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The quick/lazy way....</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
When you get to the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> A:\&gt;</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> prompt, type <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> format c: /u /q</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. That'll format the drive leaving the existing partitions intact.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The not-quite-so-quick way....</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
At the prompt, type <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> format c: /u</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. This will take significantly longer, but verifies the disk surface which could be needed.<br>
<br>
<br>
As far as installation of the operating system, I'd go with Windows XP. It really is better than 98/ME, because it actually uses the RAM you have. 98 won't actually use more than 192MB. On a clean installation, you should have no problem.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Optional steps. Skip if it's too technical....</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
I'd go to <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.ranish.com/part/">www.ranish.com/part/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> and download 2.40.00 version of the Ranish Partition Manager. Unpack just the executable to your bootdisk. You can use this program to make sure that the partitioning is correct. Read the documentation for the program, or follow onscreen instructions (it's quite intuitive) for how to operate. Launch the program by typing <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> PART</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
I would reccomend that you create a 2nd partition at the end of the drive. Say 1.5GB of space, and the rest of the drive as your C: drive. I say this because of the sheer number of times I've had to reinstall my OS. If you're only going to do it once, you don't have to do this, but repartitioning like this saves me a good 45 minutes every time I reinstall. Reboot using the bootdisk after repartitioning.<br>
<br>
Copy the contents of the XP CD to your D: drive using the command <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> xcopy e:\i386 d: /s</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. Doing this will speed the installation of the O/S immensely. It will also save you the trouble next time you have to reinstall the OS (you can just <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> format C: /q /u</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> and reinstall), and you won't have to worry about inserting the XP CDROM when installing/removing Windows components. Just tell it to look in <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  D:\i386</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Back to the installation....</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Depending on which route you chose, you are now ready to install the O/S. If you chose not to repartition the drives as described above (shame!) then just reboot with the XP CD in your CDROM drive and proceed with the onscreen instructions.<br>
<br>
If you chose to repartition the drive as suggested above, reboot off your floppy disk. Then type the following commands:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> D:<br>
cd \i386<br>
winnt</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
and follow the onscreen instructions for installation.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> After the installation....</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
You may notice that Safe Mode and Safe Mode: Command Prompt Only are relatively useless under XP. Command prompt specifically, because it is exactly the same as normal safe mode, except it has a command window shell instead of explorer. You can prove this by clicking the X on the command prompt window, and then CTRL-ALT-DELETE. Click on New Task... and type EXPLORER as the command line.<br>
<br>
You can install a more useful version of &quot;safe mode&quot; called the Recovery Console. Insert your XP CDROM in the drive if you installed off the CD. Then click Start &gt; Run... and type in the command <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> d:\i386\winnt32.exe /cmdcons</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to install the Recovery Console. This console can be used to help recover from more critical failures within the O/S, without having to reinstall Windows.<br>
<br>
The command to install the Recovery Console will be the same either way, because if you repartition as I <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> strongly suggest</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> then your install directory will be D:\i386. If, however, you leave it as one big C: drive, then the CDROM will be D:, and again, the install directory will be D:\i386.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
The installation of Windows 98 is virtually identical. The only differences are that the 98 directory is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> \win98</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, the executable to install is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> setup.exe</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, and the Recovery Console doesn't exist.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
And some real numbers from my computer so you understand why I so strongly suggest repartionning.....<br>
<br>
Installation of Windows 98 from CD: 45 minutes.<br>
Installation of Windows 98 from HDD (partitionned as suggested above): 5 minutes. Including copying from CD to HDD.<br>
Installation of XP Professional from CD: 2 hours.<br>
Installation of XP Professional from HDD: 30 minutes.<br>
